<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06203020 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06203020 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photos (2); PHOTO: Mandela; PHOTO: Buthelezi  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  SOUTH-AFRICA; BLACK; ORGANIZATION; CONTROVERSY; GOVERNMENT; MONEY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The leader of a black group that received secret government funds sought todistance himself from the scandal Saturday, asserting his politicalindependence and denying knowledge of the payments.;    But furor raged overthe disclosure of Pretoria's covert aid to the Inkatha Freedom Party, withanti-apartheid leaders urging renewed economic sanctions and conservativesdemanding a full inquiry.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  PRETORIA CAN'T BUY LOYALTY, GROUP SAYSBLACK GROUP'S LEADER SHRUGS OFF DONATIONS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Credibility threatened;  It also threatens the credibility of Inkatha andthe government soon after some foreign leaders agreed to lift embargoes. Also,hopes of negotiations to end white-minority rule have been raised by theelection of moderates to lead the African National Congress, Inkatha's mainrival.;    ANC leader Nelson Mandela had said the incident could lead to abreak in relations between the government and the ANC. Supporters of the ANCand Inkatha, the country's two major black opposition groups, have clashed intownship battles that have claimed 6,000 lives in five years.;    Inkathaleader Mangosuthu Buthelezi said he had no plans for an alliance with thegoverning party and stressed his organization's independent role.;    Theparty &quot;has not and is not negotiating for an alliance with any other politicalparty,&quot; Buthelezi said, opening the group's 16th general conference in theeastern city of Ulundi.;    Buthelezi said the payments were made to anInkatha bank account set up to receive contributions from anonymous donors,and he had no knowledge of contributors.;    The ANC had often claimed Inkathawas aided by the government, which denied the charges. But Law and OrderMinister Adriaan Vlok on Friday disclosed that the government gave Inkatha atotal of $100,000 in late 1989 and early 1990 to pay for two rallies.;    'Youare a liar';  Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu, winner of the 1984 Nobel PeacePrize for his anti-apartheid efforts, led calls for Vlok and Defense MinisterGen. Magnus Malan to resign. Tutu spoke before 22,000 people at the funeral oftwo slain ANC members.;    &quot;You have shown us that you are a liar,&quot; Tutu saidof Vlok. &quot;You said you did not support any one of the two groups.&quot;;    JoeSlovo, the Communist Party head who also is an ANC leader, said: &quot;We are tiredof your policy of blood and smiles. We have always known that they were usingInkatha as a private political and military army in an attempt to destroy us.. . . Now the truth is out.&quot;  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Johannesburg, South AfRica  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910721  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  13A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  404  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday July 21, 199100203020,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>